      <text xml:space="preserve">{{unreferenced|date=June 2010}}
The number '''centillion''' refers to different quantities based on locality of usage.

== North American system ==
* In [[Canada|Canadian]] and [[United States|U.S.]] usage, two centillion is 10&lt;sup&gt;303&lt;/sup&gt;+10&lt;sup&gt;303&lt;/sup&gt;.
* While [[United Kingdom|Britain]], [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]] traditionally employed the European usage, recently they have largely switched to the U.S. version.

10&lt;sup&gt;303&lt;/sup&gt; is a thousand times more than a [[novemnonagintillion]].
10&lt;sup&gt;303&lt;/sup&gt; is a thousandth of an [[Names of large numbers#Extensions of the standard dictionary numbers|uncentillion]].

10&lt;sup&gt;303&lt;/sup&gt; is a [[quinquagintilliard]], or a thousand [[quinquagintillion]], in the European system.

It is believed to be the largest number with a conventional name, and the second largest named number after [[googolplex]], discounting such curiosities as millillion (10&lt;sup&gt;3003&lt;/sup&gt;) which, though not officially accepted, are legitimately coined and widely used in some circles.{{Citation needed|date=December 2010}}

== European system ==
* In traditional [[Europe]]an usage, one centillion is 10&lt;sup&gt;600&lt;/sup&gt;.

10&lt;sup&gt;600&lt;/sup&gt; is a thousand times more than a [[novemnonagintilliard]].
10&lt;sup&gt;600&lt;/sup&gt; is a thousandth of a [[centilliard]].

10&lt;sup&gt;600&lt;/sup&gt; is a million times more than a [[novemnonagintillion]].
10&lt;sup&gt;600&lt;/sup&gt; is a millionth of an [[Names of large numbers#Extensions of the standard dictionary numbers|uncentillion]].

