  <page>
    <title>Concept album</title>
    <id>7527</id>
    <revision>
      <id>430194952</id>
      <timestamp>2011-05-21T14:04:51Z</timestamp>
      <contributor>
        <username>SmackBot</username>
        <id>433328</id>
      </contributor>
      <minor />
      <comment>Dated {{Refimprove}}. (Build p611)</comment>
      <text xml:space="preserve">{{Refimprove|date=May 2011}}
In music, a '''concept album''' is an [[album]] that is &quot;unified by a theme, which can be instrumental, compositional, narrative, or lyrical&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Shuker, Roy: ''Popular Music: The Key Concepts'', page 5. ISBN 0-415-28425-2. 2002.&lt;/ref&gt; Commonly, concept albums tend to incorporate preconceived musical or lyrical ideas rather than being [[musical improvisation|improvised]] or composed in the studio, with all songs contributing to [[narrative|a single overall theme or unified story]]. This is in contrast to the practice of an artist or group releasing an album consisting of a number of unconnected (lyrically or otherwise) songs performed by the artist.

== History ==
=== 1960s ===

Perhaps the first examples from rock were the albums of [[The Ventures]]. Starting from 1961's ''Colorful Ventures'' (each song had a color in the title), the group became known for issuing records throughout the 1960s whose tracks revolved around central themes, including surf music, country, outer space, TV themes, and psychedelic music.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=iDesign Studios | www.idesignstudios.com | copyright © 2002 iDesign Studios. All rights reserved. |url=http://www.sandcastlevi.com/ventures/venthst.htm |title=The Fabulous Ventures - Band History |publisher=Sandcastle V.I. |date= |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; Ray Charles also issued his ''[[Modern Sounds in Country and Western Music|Modern Sounds]]'' recordings, which departed from his well-known R&amp;B and soul style to conceptually country music records.

In 1966, several rock releases were arguably concept albums in the sense that they presented a set of thematically-linked songs - and they also instigated other rock artists to consider using the album format in a similar fashion: The Beach Boys' ''[[Pet Sounds]]'' was a musical portrayal of [[Brian Wilson]]'s state of mind at the time (and a major inspiration to [[Paul McCartney]]). Although it has a unified theme in its emotional content, the writers (Brian Wilson and Tony Asher) have said continuously that it was not necessarily intended to be a narrative. However, later in 1966, Brian Wilson began work on the ''[[Smile (Beach Boys album)|Smile]]'' album, which ''was'' intended as a narrative. The album was scrapped before completion, only to be revived in the 2000s. The [[Mothers of Invention]]'s sardonic farce about rock music and America as a whole, ''[[Freak Out!]]'' by [[Frank Zappa]] and ''[[Face to Face (The Kinks album)|Face to Face]]'' by [[The Kinks]], the first collection of [[Ray Davies]]'s idiosyncratic character studies of ordinary people are conceptually oriented albums. However, out of the albums above, only Pet Sounds attracted a huge commercial audience.

This all changed with [[The Beatles]]' most celebrated album ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' in June 1967. With the release of ''Sgt. Pepper'', the notion of the concept album came to the forefront of the popular and critical mind, with the earlier prototypes and examples from [[Traditional pop music]] and other genres sometimes forgotten.

In fact, as pointed out by many critics since its original reception, ''Sgt. Pepper'' is a concept album only by some definitions of the term. There was, at some stage during the making of the album an attempt to relate the material to firstly the idea of aging, then as an obscure radio play about the life of an ex-army bandsman and his shortcomings. These concepts were lost in the final production. While debate exists over the extent to which ''Sgt. Pepper'' qualifies as a true concept album, there is no doubt that its reputation as such helped inspire other artists to produce concept albums of their own, and inspired the public to anticipate them. Lennon and McCartney distanced themselves from the &quot;concept album&quot; tag as applied to that album.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=Posted Nov 01, 2003 12:00 AM |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6595610/1_sgt_peppers_lonely_hearts_club_band |title=1) Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band: Rolling Stone |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2003-11-01 |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

''[[Days of Future Passed]]'', released the same year as ''Sgt. Pepper's'', was fellow UK musicians The Moody Blues' first foray into the concept album.  Originally presented with an opportunity to rock out [[Antonín Dvořák|Dvořák']]s [[Symphony No. 9 (Dvořák)|Symphony No. 9 &quot;From the New World&quot;]] by their new stereophonic label, the band instead forged ahead to unify their own orchestral-based threads of a day in the life of a common man.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last = Eder|first = Bruce|authorlink = |coauthors = |title = The Moody Blues: Biography| work = |publisher = AMG [All Music Group, a subsidiary of Macrovision]| year = 2009|url = {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p4948/biography|pure_url=yes}}| format = |doi = |accessdate = 2009-07-28}}&lt;/ref&gt;

''[[The Who Sell Out]]'' by [[The Who]] followed with its concept of a [[pirate radio]] broadcast. Within the record, joke commercials recorded by the band and actual [[jingle]]s from recently outlawed pirate radio station [[Wonderful Radio London|Radio London]] were interspersed between the songs, ranging from pop songs to [[hard rock]] and [[psychedelic rock]], culminating with a mini-opera titled &quot;Rael&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|author=Posted Nov 01, 2003 12:00 AM |url=http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/6598681/113_the_who_sell_out |title=113) The Who Sell Out: Rolling Stone |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=2003-11-01 |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In October 1967, the British group [[Nirvana (UK band)|Nirvana]] released ''[[The Story of Simon Simopath]]'' (subtitled &quot;A Science Fiction Pantomime&quot;), an album that tells the story of the title character. It was only a moderate commercial success. The album ''[[S.F. Sorrow]]'' (released in December 1968) by British group the [[Pretty Things]] is generally considered to be among the first creatively successful rock concept albums - in that each song is part of an overarching unified concept – the life story of the main character, Sebastian Sorrow.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/reviews/article/24787/prettythings-sf |title=The Pretty Things: S.F. Sorrow - PopMatters Music Review |publisher=PopMatters |date=2009-01-06 |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Released in April 1969, was the [[rock opera]] ''[[Tommy (rock opera)|Tommy]]'' composed by [[Pete Townshend]] and performed by [[The Who]]. This acclaimed work was presented over [[double album|two discs]] (still unusual in those days) and it took the idea of thematically based albums to a much higher appreciation by both critics and the public. It was also the first ''story-based'' concept album of the rock era (as distinct from the ''song-cycle'' style album) to enjoy commercial success. The Who went on to further explorations of the concept album format with their follow-up project ''[[Lifehouse (rock opera)|Lifehouse]]'', which was abandoned before completion, and with their 1973 rock opera, ''[[Quadrophenia]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608004122/Pete-Townshend.html |title=Pete Townshend Biography - Discography, Music, Lyrics, Album, CD, Career, Famous Works, and Awards |publisher=Musicianguide.com |date= |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Five months after the release of ''Tommy'', [[The Kinks]] released another concept album ''[[Arthur (Or the Decline and Fall of the British Empire)]]'' (September 1969), written by [[Ray Davies]], considered by some a rock opera but originally conceived as the score for a proposed but never realised BBC television drama. It was the first of several concept albums released by the band through the first few years of the 1970s. These were: ''[[Lola Versus Powerman and the Moneygoround, Part One]]'' (1970), ''[[Muswell Hillbillies]]'' (1971), ''[[Preservation: Act 1]]'' (1973), ''[[Preservation: Act 2]]'' (1974), ''[[Soap Opera (album)|Soap Opera]]'' (1975) and ''[[Schoolboys in Disgrace]]'' (1976).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.musicianguide.com/biographies/1608001298/Ray-Davies.html |title=Ray Davies Biography - Discography, Music, Lyrics, Album, CD, Career, Famous Works, and Awards |publisher=Musicianguide.com |date= |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

=== 1970s ===
Concept albums are considered ''de rigueur'' in the [[progressive rock]] genre of the 1970s. [[Pink Floyd]] recast itself from its 1960s guise as a psychedelic band into a commercial success with its series of concept albums, most famously with ''[[The Dark Side of the Moon]]'' (which, according to the RIAA, is the third best selling album in history) and later with the double album rock opera ''[[The Wall]]''.

From 1975 to 1979, a Canadian progressive power trio, [[Rush (band)|Rush]], released three albums containing sidelong epics, regarded by some as concept albums (though not actually concept albums by strict definition of the term; that is, none of the other songs on the album have anything to do with each other or the 20-minute sidelong epic, so there is no pervasive concept or story). The first of which was released in 1975, titled ''[[Caress of Steel]]''. The second was their break through album, ''[[2112 (album)|2112]]'', released the following year in 1976. Their third was released in 1979, ''[[Hemispheres (Rush album)|Hemispheres]]''. Rush is working on another concept album titled ''[[Clockwork Angels]]'', to be released in late 2011/early 2012.

[[Yes (band)|Yes]] also put out concept albums during the 70s, most notably ''[[Tales from Topographic Oceans]]'', which would become a defining album of prog rock but whose critical backlash would lead to the genre's decline in popularity and the rise of punk rock.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.warr.org/yes.html |title=Yes |publisher=Warr.org |date= |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.punk77.co.uk/punkhistory/whendinosaursromaedtheearth.htm |title=History Of Punk - Genesis, ELP &amp; Yes |publisher=Punk77.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;
The group's keyboardist [[Rick Wakeman]] released many concept albums on his own, most notably ''[[The Six Wives of Henry VIII (album)|The Six Wives of Henry VIII]]'' and ''[[Journey to the Centre of the Earth (album)|Journey to the Centre of the Earth]]'', which was based on the novel by [[Jules Verne]].

Another progressive rock act, [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], released the concept album ''[[The Lamb Lies Down on Broadway]]'' in 1974, a double disc that told the story of the street punk Rael. Rock musician [[David Bowie]] also made three popular concept albums, ''[[Aladdin Sane]]'', ''[[Diamond Dogs]]'' and ''[[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders From Mars]]''. The latter is about a fictional character, Ziggy Stardust and his band.

In the 1970s and 80s, [[The Alan Parsons Project]] was a British progressive rock group which specialized entirely in concept albums.

=== 1980s ===
Though the progressive rock genre was beginning to decrease in popularity, concept albums had become a medium that continued. The progressive bands that were still around were still having major successes with concept albums. [[Styx (band)|Styx]] continued to have multiplatinum albums with their 1981 release ''[[Paradise Theater (album)|Paradise Theater]]'' (a concept album about a decaying theater in Chicago which became a metaphor for childhood and American culture) and 1983's ''[[Kilroy Was Here (album)|Kilroy Was Here]]'' (a science fiction rock opera about a future where moralists imprison rockers).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/features/article/8636/concept-albums-are-once-again-in-vogue-in-the-digital-age/ |title=Music Feature &amp;#124; Concept Albums Are Once Again in Vogue in the Digital Age |publisher=PopMatters |date= |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In the 1980s, the concept album became popular among [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] bands bands like [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], and their bombastic offering, 1981's ''[[Music from &quot;The Elder&quot;]]'', which went on to become the group's poorest selling and charting album in their history. [[Queensrÿche]] fared better later the decade, releasing the rock opera  ''[[Operation: Mindcrime]]'' in 1988; which tells a story of a young man, Nikki, awoken from a coma suddenly remembering work done as a political assassin.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/columns/begrand/060316.shtml |title=Columns &amp;#124; Adrien Begrand &amp;#124; Blood and Thunder &amp;#124; The Queen Isn't Dead |publisher=PopMatters |date=2006-03-16 |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[King Diamond (band)|King Diamond]] gained cult status during the 1980s releasing mostly all concept albums. Releases such as ''[[Abigail (album)|Abigail]]'', ''[[Them (King Diamond album)|&quot;Them&quot;]]'', and ''[[The Eye (King Diamond album)|The Eye]]'' told elaborate sagas of horror and the [[supernatural]].

In 1985 Kerrang! magazine ran a coverstory on [[Phenomena]],&lt;ref&gt;http://www.projectphenomena.com&lt;/ref&gt; announcing &quot;the return of the concept album&quot;. Tom Galley had started the project, and together with his brother Mell and Metalhammer magazine founder Wilfried Rimensberger developed it into an international multi-media rock music project with contributions from a string of rock superstars, that, apart from so far a total of 5 albums, produced the Dreamrunner album and an ongoing following around the world. Phenomena's main story lines are dealing with the super-natural and unexplaned, that are also turned in to scripts for musical, rock opera stage productions, feature films and video games. [[Iron Maiden]] also released several concept albums including ''[[Seventh Son of a Seventh Son]]''; which follows the folklore and myths of a seventh son of a seventh son having mystical powers.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.maidenfans.com/imc/?url=album07_ssoass/commentary07_ssoass&amp;link=albums&amp;lang=eng |title=The Iron Maiden Commentary |publisher=Maidenfans.com |date=1988-04-11 |accessdate=2009-01-18}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}&lt;/ref&gt;

===1990s===
In the 1990s prog rock had all but faded from popular music. With the advent of [[alternative rock]], however, a number of artists still continued to use the format.

In that decade the rock band [[Marilyn Manson]] created three [[rock opera]] concept albums, namely, ''[[Antichrist Superstar]]'' (1996), ''[[Mechanical Animals]]'' (1998) and ''[[Holy Wood (In the Shadow of the Valley of Death)|Holy Wood]]'' (2000), which formed an ambitious concept trilogy. Though each one came with individual conceptual backgrounds, they are also meant to be taken together to form a larger abstract storyline. The albums were released in reverse order thus in the larger overarching 'fourth storyline' is divulged in reverse chronological order.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal |first=Tom|last=Lanham |date=2000-11 |year= |month= |title=Marilyn Manson: Absinthe Makes The Heart Grow Fonder |trans_title= |journal=[[Alternative Press]] |volume= |series= |issue=#148 |page= |pages=76–86 |at= |chapter= |location= |publisher= |editor1-first= |editor1-last= |editor1-link= |accessdate=2010-11-22 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last=Basham |first=David |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431695/19991216/marilyn_manson.jhtml|title= Manson To Walk In The &quot;Valley Of Death&quot; For Next LP |publisher=[[MTV News]] |date= 1999-12-16|accessdate=2010-11-17}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;MTV Marilyn Manson Tweaks Holy Wood Plans&quot;&gt;{{cite web|last=Basham |first=David |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431690/marilyn-manson-tweaks-holy-wood-plans.jhtml |title=Marilyn Manson Tweaks &quot;Holy Wood&quot; Plans |publisher=MTV News |date=2000-02-29|accessdate=2011-03-22}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In 1999, progressive metal band [[Dream Theater]] released ''[[Metropolis Pt. 2: Scenes from a Memory]]'', a story concept album.  This was a specific follow-up to a song called &quot;Metropolis Pt. 1: The Miracle and the Sleeper,&quot; which was released on the band's 1992 breakthrough album, ''[[Images and Words]]''.  While &quot;Pt. 1&quot; introduced a story, further parts of the &quot;Metropolis&quot; story were unseen on that album or subsequent releases for seven years.  Although the band had created a twenty-minute follow-up to Part 1 in the mid-nineties, it hadn't been released.  After the band gained complete creative control from their record company, they decided to expand their follow-up of the Metropolis story into a full album: ''[[Metropolis Pt. 2: Scenes from a Memory]]''.  This album builds on concepts introduced in Part 1, both lyrically and musically.  Although it did not achieve the same levels of commercial success as the band's later releases (it reached #73 on the [[Billboard 200]]), it has been hailed by many fans and critics as Dream Theater's masterpiece and the band's defining album.

===2000s and 2010s===
With the advent of the [[World Wide Web]] and other multimedia technologies, bands such as [[The Smashing Pumpkins]] (with the album ''[[Machina/The Machines of God]]''), [[Coheed And Cambria]] (with the [[Amory Wars]] as a backing story), and [[Nine Inch Nails]] (with the album ''[[Year Zero (album)|Year Zero]]'')&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|last=Montgomery |first=James |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1552470/20070215/nine_inch_nails.jhtml |title=Nine Inch Nails' Conspiracy Campaign - News Story &amp;#124; Music, Celebrity, Artist News &amp;#124; MTV News |publisher=Mtv.com |date=2007-02-15 |accessdate=2009-01-18}}&lt;/ref&gt; exploited emergent cultural phenomena such as the [[alternate reality game]] to provide additional web-based content beyond that on the album itself.

Also in the 2000s, [[pop punk]] outfit [[Green Day]] produced two [[Grammy]]-winning concept albums, namely, 2004's ''[[American Idiot]]'' and 2009's ''[[21st Century Breakdown]]''.&lt;ref&gt;''“21st Century Breakdown” follows Green Day’s “American Idiot,” the politically charged concept album from 2004 that has sold more than five million copies domestically and an estimated 12 million worldwide.'', [http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/03/arts/music/03pare.html The Morning After ‘American Idiot’], ''[[The New York Times]]''&lt;/ref&gt; In 2010 ''[[American Idiot]]'' became the first [[American Idiot (musical)|punk rock opera]] to make it to [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation  | last = Hurwitt  | first = Robert  | title = Green Day's hits turn into Berkeley Rep musical  | newspaper = San Francisco Chronicle  | date = 2009-03-31  | url = http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2009/03/31/DD8R16NNSN.DTL}}&lt;/ref&gt; where it has garnered two [[Tony Awards]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Tonys&quot;&gt;{{cite web|title=Who's Nominated?|url=http://www.tonyawards.com/en_US/nominees/index.html|work=Tony Awards|publisher=IBM Corp.|accessdate=13 June 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

American metal band [[Symphony X]] included the sidelong epic ''[[The Divine Wings of Tragedy]]'' in the eponymous album released in 1997. In October 2000, the concept album ''[[V-The New Mythology Suite]]'', the fifth studio album of the band, was released to critical acclaim. The story of the album is a mix of ancient Greek and Egyptian mythology, mixed with Edgar Cayce's visions of Atlantis, and explores the concept of &quot;history repeating itself&quot;, and the view of modern technological advances as a rediscovery of the developments of the Atlanteans.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.symphonyx.com/cd_v_story.html The story behind ''&quot;V: The New Mythology Suite&quot;'']&lt;/ref&gt;

[[Punk rock]] band [[Against Me!]] released their first concept album in 2005, ''[[Searching for a Former Clarity]]'', praised for its &quot;confessional lyrics&quot; about dying from a [[Social effects of rock music#Sex and drugs|rockstar lifestyle]].&lt;ref&gt;http://www.self-titledmag.com/home/2010/07/20/the-self-titled-interview-against-me/&lt;/ref&gt;

The American power metal band [[Kamelot]] released two concept albums based on ''[[Goethe's Faust]]'' which are entitled ''[[Epica (album)|Epica]]'' (2003) and ''[[The Black Halo]]'' (2005).

In 2007 rapper, [[Jay-Z]], released [[American Gangster (album)|American Gangster]], his first concept album, inspired by the [[American Gangster (film)|movie of the same name]], it was met with critical praise.

In the 2000s, the progressive rock band [[30 Seconds to Mars]] released two concept albums, ''[[30 Seconds to Mars (album)|30 Seconds to Mars]]'' (2002) and ''[[This Is War]]'' (2009). Also in the 2000s, [[My Chemical Romance]] released several concept albums, the most popular being ''[[Three Cheers for Sweet Revenge]]'' and ''[[The Black Parade]]''.

In addition, Grammy-winning [[Heavy metal music|metal]] band [[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]] has released three concept albums, ''[[Leviathan (album)|Leviathan]]'', ''[[Blood Mountain (album)|Blood Mountain]]'', and ''[[Crack the Skye]]'', which, along with their debut album, ''[[Remission (Mastodon album)|Remission]]'', make up a quadrilogy, each representing its own element: water, earth, air, and fire, respectively.

In May of 2010, [[Janelle Monae]] released her debut album ''[[The ArchAndroid]]'' to general acclaim. This album is the sequel to her 2007 EP ''[[Metropolis: Suite I (The Chase)]]'', both of which are parts of Monae's &quot;Metropolis&quot; concept album series that tell the story of android Cindy Mayweather and her struggle to break free of the bonds of her oppressive society.

In 2009, [[Silverstein]], a Canadian [[post-hardcore]] and [[alternative rock]] band, released &quot;[[A Shipwreck in the Sand]]&quot;. This album has many tracks which blend into the next, and is divided into four &quot;chapters&quot;. The Album tells a story of love, hate, and betrayal through the songs.

''[[The Defamation of Strickland Banks]]'' is a concept album from British rapper Ben Drew, better known by his stage name [[Plan B]] which was released on 12 April and topped the UK charts at #1 in the album's release year of 2010.

In August of the same year, [[Arcade Fire]] released ''[[The Suburbs (Arcade Fire album)|The Suburbs]]'' which went on to win the Grammy award for [[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|album of the year]].

